# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: model-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:model-theory/compactness-theorem] In mathematical logic, the **compactness theorem** states that a set of first-order sentences has a model if and only if every finite subset of it has a model.
[src:model-theory/compactness-theorem] This theorem is an important tool in model theory, as it provides a useful (but generally not effective) method for constructing models of any set of sentences that is finitely consistent.
[src:model-theory/compactness-theorem] The compactness theorem for the propositional calculus is a consequence of Tychonoff's theorem (which says that the product of compact spaces is compact) applied to compact Stone spaces, hence the theorem's name.
[src:model-theory/compactness-theorem] Likewise, it is analogous to the finite intersection property characterization of compactness in topological spaces: a collection of closed sets in a compact space has a non-empty intersection if every finite subcollection has a non-empty intersection.
[src:model-theory/compactness-theorem] The compactness theorem is one of the two key properties, along with the downward Löwenheim–Skolem theorem, that is used in Lindström's theorem to characterize first-order logic.
[src:model-theory/compactness-theorem] Although there are some generalizations of the compactness theorem to non-first-order logics, the compactness theorem itself does not hold in them, except for a very limited number of examples.
[src:model-theory/compactness-theorem] Kurt Gödel proved the countable compactness theorem in 1930.
[src:model-theory/compactness-theorem] Anatoly Maltsev proved the uncountable case in 1936.
[src:model-theory/compactness-theorem] The compactness theorem has many applications in model theory; a few typical results are sketched here.
[src:model-theory/compactness-theorem] The compactness theorem implies the following result, stated by Abraham Robinson in his 1949 dissertation.
[src:model-theory/compactness-theorem] Therefore, there is a finite subset A of these sentences that is not satisfiable.
[src:model-theory/compactness-theorem] A must contain $\lnot \varphi$ because otherwise it would be satisfiable.
[src:model-theory/compactness-theorem] This means that $\varphi$ must hold in every model of $B,$ which means precisely that $\varphi$ holds in every field of characteristic greater than $k.$ This completes the proof.
[src:model-theory/compactness-theorem] The Lefschetz principle, one of the first examples of a transfer principle, extends this result.
[src:model-theory/compactness-theorem] In fact, the surjectivity conclusion remains true for any injective polynomial $F^{n}\to F^{n}$ where F is a finite field or the algebraic closure of such a field.
[src:model-theory/compactness-theorem] A second application of the compactness theorem shows that any theory that has arbitrarily large finite models, or a single infinite model, has models of arbitrary large cardinality (this is the Upward Löwenheim–Skolem theorem).
[src:model-theory/compactness-theorem] So for instance, there are nonstandard models of Peano arithmetic with uncountably many 'natural numbers'.
[src:model-theory/compactness-theorem] To achieve this, let T be the initial theory and let $\kappa$ be any cardinal number.
[src:model-theory/compactness-theorem] Add to the language of T one constant symbol for every element of $\kappa .$ Then add to T a collection of sentences that say that the objects denoted by any two distinct constant symbols from the new collection are distinct (this is a collection of $\kappa ^{2}$ sentences).
[src:model-theory/compactness-theorem] Since every *finite* subset of this new theory is satisfiable by a sufficiently large finite model of $T,$ or by any infinite model, the entire extended theory is satisfiable.
[src:model-theory/compactness-theorem] But any model of the extended theory has cardinality at least $\kappa$ .
[src:model-theory/compactness-theorem] A third application of the compactness theorem is the construction of nonstandard models of the real numbers, that is, consistent extensions of the theory of the real numbers that contain "infinitesimal" numbers.
[src:model-theory/compactness-theorem] To see this, let $\Sigma$ be a first-order axiomatization of the theory of the real numbers.
[src:model-theory/compactness-theorem] A similar argument, this time adjoining the axioms $\omega >0,\;\omega >1,\ldots ,$ etc., shows that the existence of numbers with infinitely large magnitudes cannot be ruled out by any axiomatization $\Sigma$ of the reals.
[src:model-theory/compactness-theorem] One can prove the compactness theorem using Gödel's completeness theorem, which establishes that a set of sentences is satisfiable if and only if no contradiction can be proven from it.
[src:model-theory/compactness-theorem] Since proofs are always finite and therefore involve only finitely many of the given sentences, the compactness theorem follows.
[src:model-theory/compactness-theorem] In fact, the compactness theorem is equivalent to Gödel's completeness theorem, and both are equivalent to the Boolean prime ideal theorem, a weak form of the axiom of choice.
[src:model-theory/compactness-theorem] Gödel originally proved the compactness theorem in just this way, but later some "purely semantic" proofs of the compactness theorem were found; that is, proofs that refer to *truth* instead of *provability*.
[src:model-theory/elementary-equivalence] In model theory, a branch of mathematical logic, two structures *M* and *N* of the same signature *σ* are called **elementarily equivalent** if they satisfy the same first-order *σ*-sentences.
[src:model-theory/elementary-equivalence] If *N* is a substructure of *M*, one often needs a stronger condition.
[src:model-theory/elementary-equivalence] In this case *N* is called an **elementary substructure** of *M* if every first-order *σ*-formula *φ*(*a*1, …, *a**n*) with parameters *a*1, …, *a**n* from *N* is true in *N* if and only if it is true in *M*.
[src:model-theory/elementary-equivalence] If *N* is an elementary substructure of *M*, then *M* is called an **elementary extension** of *N*.
[src:model-theory/elementary-equivalence] An embedding *h*: *N* → *M* is called an **elementary embedding** of *N* into *M* if *h*(*N*) is an elementary substructure of *M*.
[src:model-theory/elementary-equivalence] A substructure *N* of *M* is elementary if and only if it passes the **Tarski–Vaught test**: every first-order formula *φ*(*x*, *b*1, …, *b**n*) with parameters in *N* that has a solution in *M* also has a solution in *N* when evaluated in *M*.
[src:model-theory/elementary-equivalence] One can prove that two structures are elementarily equivalent with the Ehrenfeucht–Fraïssé games.
[src:model-theory/elementary-equivalence] Elementary embeddings are used in the study of large cardinals, including rank-into-rank.
[src:model-theory/elementary-equivalence] Two structures *M* and *N* of the same signature *σ* are **elementarily equivalent** if every first-order sentence (formula without free variables) over *σ* is true in *M* if and only if it is true in *N*, i.e. if *M* and *N* have the same complete first-order theory.
[src:model-theory/elementary-equivalence] If *M* and *N* are elementarily equivalent, one writes *M* ≡ *N*.
[src:model-theory/elementary-equivalence] A first-order theory is complete if and only if any two of its models are elementarily equivalent.
[src:model-theory/elementary-equivalence] For example, consider the language with one binary relation symbol '<'.
[src:model-theory/elementary-equivalence] The model **R** of real numbers with its usual order and the model **Q** of rational numbers with its usual order are elementarily equivalent, since they both interpret '<' as an unbounded dense linear ordering.
[src:model-theory/elementary-equivalence] This is sufficient to ensure elementary equivalence, because the theory of unbounded dense linear orderings is complete, as can be shown by the Łoś–Vaught test.
[src:model-theory/elementary-equivalence] More generally, any first-order theory with an infinite model has non-isomorphic, elementarily equivalent models, which can be obtained via the Löwenheim–Skolem theorem.
[src:model-theory/elementary-equivalence] Thus, for example, there are non-standard models of Peano arithmetic, which contain other objects than just the numbers 0, 1, 2, etc., and yet are elementarily equivalent to the standard model.
[src:model-theory/elementary-equivalence] This definition first appears in Tarski, Vaught (1957).
[src:model-theory/elementary-equivalence] It follows that *N* is a substructure of *M*.
[src:model-theory/elementary-equivalence] If *N* is a substructure of *M*, then both *N* and *M* can be interpreted as structures in the signature *σ**N* consisting of *σ* together with a new constant symbol for every element of *N*.
[src:model-theory/elementary-equivalence] Then *N* is an elementary substructure of *M* if and only if *N* is a substructure of *M* and *N* and *M* are elementarily equivalent as *σ**N*-structures.
[src:model-theory/elementary-equivalence] If *N* is an elementary substructure of *M*, one writes *N* $\preceq$ *M* and says that *M* is an **elementary extension** of *N*: *M* $\succeq$ *N*.
[src:model-theory/elementary-equivalence] The downward Löwenheim–Skolem theorem gives a countable elementary substructure for any infinite first-order structure in at most countable signature; the upward Löwenheim–Skolem theorem gives elementary extensions of any infinite first-order structure of arbitrarily large cardinality.
[src:model-theory/elementary-equivalence] The **Tarski–Vaught test** (or **Tarski–Vaught criterion**) is a necessary and sufficient condition for a substructure *N* of a structure *M* to be an elementary substructure.
[src:model-theory/elementary-equivalence] It can be useful for constructing an elementary substructure of a large structure.
[src:model-theory/elementary-equivalence] Let *M* be a structure of signature *σ* and *N* a substructure of *M*.
[src:model-theory/elementary-equivalence] Every elementary embedding is a strong homomorphism, and it induces an isomorphism between *N* and an elementary substructure of *M*.
[src:model-theory/elementary-equivalence] Elementary embeddings are the most important maps in model theory.
[src:model-theory/elementary-equivalence] In set theory, elementary embeddings whose domain is *V* (the universe of set theory) play an important role in the theory of large cardinals (see also Critical point).
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] In mathematical logic, a **theory** (also called a **formal theory**) is a set of sentences in a formal language.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] In most scenarios a deductive system is first understood from context, giving rise to a formal system that combines the language with deduction rules.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] An element $\phi \in T$ of a deductively closed theory T is then called a theorem of the theory.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] In many deductive systems there is usually a subset $\Sigma \subseteq T$ that is called "the set of axioms" of the theory T , in which case the deductive system is also called an "axiomatic system".
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] By definition, every axiom is automatically a theorem.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] A **first-order theory** is a set of first-order sentences (theorems) recursively obtained by the inference rules of the system applied to the set of axioms.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] When defining theories for foundational purposes, additional care must be taken, as normal set-theoretic language may not be appropriate.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] The construction of a theory begins by specifying a definite non-empty *conceptual class* ${\mathcal {E}}$ , the elements of which are called *statements*.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] These initial statements are often called the *primitive elements* or *elementary* statements of the theory—to distinguish them from other statements that may be derived from them.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] A theory ${\mathcal {T}}$ is a conceptual class consisting of certain of these elementary statements.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] The elementary statements that belong to ${\mathcal {T}}$ are called the *elementary theorems* of ${\mathcal {T}}$ and are said to be *true*.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] In this way, a theory can be seen as a way of designating a subset of ${\mathcal {E}}$ that only contain statements that are true.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] This general way of designating a theory stipulates that the truth of any of its elementary statements is not known without reference to ${\mathcal {T}}$ .
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] Thus the same elementary statement may be true with respect to one theory but false with respect to another.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] This is reminiscent of the case in ordinary language where statements such as "He is an honest person" cannot be judged true or false without interpreting who "he" is, and, for that matter, what an "honest person" is under this theory.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] A theory is said to be a *deductive theory* if ${\mathcal {T}}$ is an inductive class, which is to say that its content is based on some formal deductive system and that some of its elementary statements are taken as axioms.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] In a deductive theory, any sentence that is a logical consequence of one or more of the axioms is also a sentence of that theory.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] A **syntactically consistent theory** is a theory from which not every sentence in the underlying language can be proven (with respect to some deductive system, which is usually clear from context).
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] In a deductive system (such as first-order logic) that satisfies the principle of explosion, this is equivalent to requiring that there is no sentence φ such that both φ and its negation can be proven from the theory.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] A **satisfiable theory** is a theory that has a model.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] This means there is a structure *M* that satisfies every sentence in the theory.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] Any satisfiable theory is syntactically consistent, because the structure satisfying the theory will satisfy exactly one of φ and the negation of φ, for each sentence φ.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] A **consistent theory** is sometimes defined to be a syntactically consistent theory, and sometimes defined to be a satisfiable theory.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] For first-order logic, the most important case, it follows from the completeness theorem that the two meanings coincide.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] In other logics, such as second-order logic, there are syntactically consistent theories that are not satisfiable, such as ω-inconsistent theories.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] A complete consistent theory (or just a **complete theory**) is a consistent theory *${\mathcal {T}}$* such that for every sentence φ in its language, either φ is provable from *${\mathcal {T}}$* or *${\mathcal {T}}$* $\cup$ {φ} is inconsistent.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] For theories closed under logical consequence, this means that for every sentence φ, either φ or its negation is contained in the theory.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] An **incomplete theory** is a consistent theory that is not complete.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] An *interpretation of a theory* is the relationship between a theory and some subject matter when there is a many-to-one correspondence between certain elementary statements of the theory, and certain statements related to the subject matter.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] If every elementary statement in the theory has a correspondent it is called a *full interpretation*, otherwise it is called a *partial interpretation*.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] Each structure has several associated theories.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] The **complete theory** of a structure *A* is the set of all first-order sentences over the signature of *A* that are satisfied by *A*.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] More generally, the **theory** of *K*, a class of σ-structures, is the set of all first-order σ-sentences that are satisfied by all structures in *K*, and is denoted by Th(*K*).
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] These notions can also be defined with respect to other logics.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] For each σ-structure *A*, there are several associated theories in a larger signature σ' that extends σ by adding one new constant symbol for each element of the domain of *A*.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] (If the new constant symbols are identified with the elements of *A* that they represent, σ' can be taken to be σ $\cup$ A.) The cardinality of σ' is thus the larger of the cardinality of σ and the cardinality of *A*.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] The **diagram** of *A* consists of all atomic or negated atomic σ'-sentences that are satisfied by *A* and is denoted by diag*A*.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] The **positive diagram** of *A* is the set of all atomic σ'-sentences that *A* satisfies.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] The **elementary diagram** of *A* is the set eldiag*A* of *all* first-order σ'-sentences that are satisfied by *A* or, equivalently, the complete (first-order) theory of the natural expansion of *A* to the signature σ'.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] A first-order theory ${\mathcal {QS}}$ is a set of sentences in a first-order formal language ${\mathcal {Q}}$ .
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] There are many formal derivation ("proof") systems for first-order logic.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] These include Hilbert-style deductive systems, natural deduction, the sequent calculus, the tableaux method and resolution.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] A formula *A* is a **syntactic consequence** of a first-order theory ${\mathcal {QS}}$ if there is a derivation of *A* using only formulas in ${\mathcal {QS}}$ as non-logical axioms.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] Such a formula *A* is also called a theorem of ${\mathcal {QS}}$ .
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] The notation " ${\mathcal {QS}}\vdash A$ " indicates *A* is a theorem of ${\mathcal {QS}}$ .
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] An **interpretation** of a first-order theory provides a semantics for the formulas of the theory.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] An interpretation is said to satisfy a formula if the formula is true according to the interpretation.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] A **model** of a first-order theory ${\mathcal {QS}}$ is an interpretation in which every formula of ${\mathcal {QS}}$ is satisfied.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] A first-order theory ${\mathcal {QS}}$ is a first-order theory with identity if ${\mathcal {QS}}$ includes the identity relation symbol "=" and the reflexivity and substitution axiom schemes for this symbol.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] A direct way to specify a theory is to define a set of axioms in a formal language.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] The theory then includes those axioms, and their provable consequences.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] Theories obtained this way include ZFC and Peano arithmetic.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] A second way to specify a theory is to begin with a structure, and let the theory be the set of sentences that are satisfied by the structure.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] The first of these, called the theory of true arithmetic, cannot be written as the set of logical consequences of any enumerable set of axioms.
[src:model-theory/first-order-theory] The theory of (**R**, +, ×, 0, 1, =) was shown by Tarski to be decidable; it is the theory of real closed fields (see Decidability of first-order theories of the real numbers for more).
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] In mathematical logic, the **Löwenheim–Skolem theorem** is a theorem on the existence and cardinality of models, named after Leopold Löwenheim and Thoralf Skolem.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] It implies that if a countable first-order theory has an infinite model, then for every infinite cardinal number *κ* it has a model of size *κ*, and that no first-order theory with an infinite model can have a unique model up to isomorphism.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] As a consequence, first-order theories are unable to control the cardinality of their infinite models.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] The (downward) Löwenheim–Skolem theorem is one of the two key properties, along with the compactness theorem, that are used in Lindström's theorem to characterize first-order logic.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] In general, the Löwenheim–Skolem theorem does not hold in stronger logics such as second-order logic.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] The theorem is often divided into two parts corresponding to the two cases above.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] The part of the theorem asserting that a structure has elementary substructures of all smaller infinite cardinalities is known as the **downward Löwenheim–Skolem Theorem**.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] The part of the theorem asserting that a structure has elementary extensions of all larger cardinalities is known as the **upward Löwenheim–Skolem Theorem**.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] Below we elaborate on the general concept of signatures and structures.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] A signature consists of a set of function symbols *S*func, a set of relation symbols *S*rel, and a function $\operatorname {ar} :S_{\operatorname {func} }\cup S_{\operatorname {rel} }\rightarrow \mathbb {N} _{0}$ representing the arity of function and relation symbols.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] (A nullary function symbol is called a constant symbol.) In the context of first-order logic, a signature is sometimes called a language.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] It is called countable if the set of function and relation symbols in it is countable, and in general the cardinality of a signature is the cardinality of the set of all the symbols it contains.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] A first-order theory consists of a fixed signature and a fixed set of sentences (formulas with no free variables) in that signature.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] Theories are often specified by giving a list of axioms that generate the theory, or by giving a structure and taking the theory to consist of the sentences satisfied by the structure.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] Given a signature *σ*, a *σ*-structure *M* is a concrete interpretation of the symbols in *σ*.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] It consists of an underlying set (often also denoted by "*M*") together with an interpretation of the function and relation symbols of *σ*.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] An interpretation of a constant symbol of *σ* in *M* is simply an element of *M*.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] More generally, an interpretation of an *n*-ary function symbol *f* is a function from *M**n* to *M*.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] Similarly, an interpretation of a relation symbol *R* is an *n*-ary relation on *M*, i.e. a subset of *M**n*.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] A substructure of a *σ*-structure *M* is obtained by taking a subset *N* of *M* which is closed under the interpretations of all the function symbols in *σ* (hence includes the interpretations of all constant symbols in *σ*), and then restricting the interpretations of the relation symbols to *N*.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] An elementary substructure is a very special case of this; in particular an elementary substructure satisfies exactly the same first-order sentences as the original structure (its elementary extension).
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] The statement given in the introduction follows immediately by taking *M* to be an infinite model of the theory.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] The proof of the upward part of the theorem also shows that a theory with arbitrarily large finite models must have an infinite model; sometimes this is considered to be part of the theorem.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] A theory is called **categorical** if it has only one model, up to isomorphism.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] This term was introduced by Veblen (1904), and for some time thereafter mathematicians hoped they could put mathematics on a solid foundation by describing a categorical first-order theory of some version of set theory.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] The Löwenheim–Skolem theorem dealt a first blow to this hope, as it implies that a first-order theory which has an infinite model cannot be categorical.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] Later, in 1931, the hope was shattered completely by Gödel's incompleteness theorem.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] Many consequences of the Löwenheim–Skolem theorem seemed counterintuitive to logicians in the early 20th century, as the distinction between first-order and non-first-order properties was not yet understood.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] One such consequence is the existence of uncountable models of true arithmetic, which satisfy every first-order induction axiom but have non-inductive subsets.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] Let **N** denote the natural numbers and **R** the reals.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] It follows from the theorem that the theory of (**N**, +, ×, 0, 1) (the theory of true first-order arithmetic) has uncountable models, and that the theory of (**R**, +, ×, 0, 1) (the theory of real closed fields) has a countable model.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] There are, of course, axiomatizations characterizing (**N**, +, ×, 0, 1) and (**R**, +, ×, 0, 1) up to isomorphism.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] The Löwenheim–Skolem theorem shows that these axiomatizations cannot be first-order.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] For example, in the theory of the real numbers, the completeness of a linear order used to characterize **R** as a complete ordered field, is a non-first-order property.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] Another consequence that was considered particularly troubling is the existence of a countable model of set theory, which nevertheless must satisfy the sentence saying the real numbers are uncountable.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] Cantor's theorem states that some sets are uncountable.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] This counterintuitive situation came to be known as Skolem's paradox; it shows that the notion of countability is not absolute.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] Applying the axiom of choice again we get a function from the first-order formulas $\varphi$ to such functions $f_{\varphi }$ .
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] Iterating F countably many times results in a closure operator $F^{\omega }$ .
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] Taking an arbitrary subset $A\subseteq M$ such that $\left\vert A\right\vert =\kappa$ , and having defined $N=F^{\omega }(A)$ , one can see that also $\left\vert N\right\vert =\kappa$ .
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] Then N is an elementary substructure of M by the Tarski–Vaught test.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] The trick used in this proof is essentially due to Skolem, who introduced function symbols for the Skolem functions $f_{\varphi }$ into the language.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] One could also define the $f_{\varphi }$ as partial functions such that $f_{\varphi }$ is defined if and only if $M\models \exists y\,\varphi (y,a_{1},\ldots ,a_{n})$ .
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] First, one extends the signature by adding a new constant symbol for every element of M .
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] The complete theory of M for the extended signature $\sigma '$ is called the *elementary diagram* of M .
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] In the next step one adds $\kappa$ many new constant symbols to the signature and adds to the elementary diagram of M the sentences $c\neq c'$ for any two distinct new constant symbols c and $c'$ .
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] Using the compactness theorem, the resulting theory is easily seen to be consistent.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] Since its models must have cardinality at least $\kappa$ , the downward part of this theorem guarantees the existence of a model N which has cardinality exactly $\kappa$ .
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] It contains an isomorphic copy of M as an elementary substructure.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] Although the (classical) Löwenheim–Skolem theorem is tied very closely to first-order logic, variants hold for other logics.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] For example, every consistent theory in second-order logic has a model smaller than the first supercompact cardinal (assuming one exists).
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] The minimum size at which a (downward) Löwenheim–Skolem–type theorem applies in a logic is known as the Löwenheim number, and can be used to characterize that logic's strength.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] Moreover, if we go beyond first-order logic, we must give up one of three things: countable compactness, the downward Löwenheim–Skolem Theorem, or the properties of an abstract logic.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] This account is based mainly on Dawson (1993).
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] To understand the early history of model theory one must distinguish between *syntactical consistency* (no contradiction can be derived using the deduction rules for first-order logic) and *satisfiability* (there is a model).
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] Somewhat surprisingly, even before the completeness theorem made the distinction unnecessary, the term *consistent* was used sometimes in one sense and sometimes in the other.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] Löwenheim's paper was actually concerned with the more general Peirce–Schröder *calculus of relatives* (relation algebra with quantifiers).
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] He also used the now antiquated notations of Ernst Schröder.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] For a summary of the paper in English and using modern notation see Brady (2000, chapter 8).
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] According to the received historical view, Löwenheim's proof was faulty because it implicitly used Kőnig's lemma without proving it, although the lemma was not yet a published result at the time.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] In a revisionist account, Badesa (2004) considers that Löwenheim's proof was complete.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] Every countable theory which is satisfiable in a model is also satisfiable in a countable model.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] Finally, Anatoly Maltsev proved the Löwenheim–Skolem theorem in its full generality (Maltsev 1936).
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] He cited a note by Skolem, according to which the theorem had been proved by Alfred Tarski in a seminar in 1928.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] Therefore, the general theorem is sometimes known as the *Löwenheim–Skolem–Tarski theorem*.
[src:model-theory/löwenheim-skolem-theorem] But Tarski did not remember his proof, and it remains a mystery how he could do it without the compactness theorem.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] In mathematical logic, **model theory** is the study of the relationship between formal theories (a collection of sentences in a formal language expressing statements about a mathematical structure) and their models (those structures in which the statements of the theory hold).
[src:model-theory/model-theory] The aspects investigated include the number and size of models of a theory, the relationship of different models to each other, and their interaction with the formal language itself.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] In particular, model theorists also investigate the sets that can be defined in a model of a theory, and the relationship of such definable sets to each other.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] As a separate discipline, model theory goes back to Alfred Tarski, who first used the term "Theory of Models" in publication in 1954.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Since the 1970s, the subject has been shaped decisively by Saharon Shelah's stability theory.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Compared to other areas of mathematical logic such as proof theory, model theory is often less concerned with formal rigour and closer in spirit to classical mathematics.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] This has prompted the comment that *"if proof theory is about the sacred, then model theory is about the profane"*.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] The applications of model theory to algebraic and Diophantine geometry reflect this proximity to classical mathematics, as they often involve an integration of algebraic and model-theoretic results and techniques.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Consequently, proof theory is syntactic in nature, in contrast to model theory, which is semantic in nature.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] This article focuses on finitary first order model theory.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] where logical formulas are to definable sets what equations are to varieties over a field.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Nonetheless, the interplay of classes of models and the sets definable in them has been crucial to the development of model theory throughout its history.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] For instance, while stability was originally introduced to classify theories by their numbers of models in a given cardinality, stability theory proved crucial to understanding the geometry of definable sets.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] A first-order *formula* is built out of atomic formulas such as $R(f(x,y),z)$ or $y=x+1$ by means of the Boolean connectives $\neg ,\land ,\lor ,\rightarrow$ and prefixing of quantifiers $\forall v$ or $\exists v$ .
[src:model-theory/model-theory] A sentence is a formula in which each occurrence of a variable is in the scope of a corresponding quantifier.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] (Note that the equality symbol has a double meaning here.) It is intuitively clear how to translate such formulas into mathematical meaning.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] In the semiring of natural numbers ${\mathcal {N}}$ , viewed as a structure with binary functions for addition and multiplication and constants for 0 and 1 of the natural numbers, for example, an element n *satisfies* the formula $\varphi$ if and only if n is a prime number.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] The formula $\psi$ similarly defines irreducibility.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] A set T of sentences is called a (first-order) theory, which takes the sentences in the set as its axioms.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] A theory is *satisfiable* if it has a *model* ${\mathcal {M}}\models T$ , i.e. a structure (of the appropriate signature) which satisfies all the sentences in the set T .
[src:model-theory/model-theory] A complete theory is a theory that contains every sentence or its negation.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] The complete theory of all sentences satisfied by a structure is also called the *theory of that structure*.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] It's a consequence of Gödel's completeness theorem (not to be confused with his incompleteness theorems) that a theory has a model if and only if it is consistent, i.e. no contradiction is proved by the theory.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Therefore, model theorists often use "consistent" as a synonym for "satisfiable".
[src:model-theory/model-theory] A signature or language is a set of non-logical symbols such that each symbol is either a constant symbol, or a function or relation symbol with a specified arity.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Note that in some literature, constant symbols are considered as function symbols with zero arity, and hence are omitted.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] A structure is a set M together with interpretations of each of the symbols of the signature as relations and functions on M (not to be confused with the formal notion of an "interpretation" of one structure in another).
[src:model-theory/model-theory] A structure ${\mathcal {N}}$ is said to model a set of first-order sentences T in the given language if each sentence in T is true in ${\mathcal {N}}$ with respect to the interpretation of the signature previously specified for ${\mathcal {N}}$ .
[src:model-theory/model-theory] (Again, not to be confused with the formal notion of an "interpretation" of one structure in another) A *model* of T is a structure that models T .
[src:model-theory/model-theory] A substructure ${\mathcal {A}}$ of a σ-structure ${\mathcal {B}}$ is a subset of its domain, closed under all functions in its signature σ, which is regarded as a σ-structure by restricting all functions and relations in σ to the subset.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] This generalises the analogous concepts from algebra; for instance, a subgroup is a substructure in the signature with multiplication and inverse.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] In particular, if $\varphi$ is a sentence and ${\mathcal {A}}$ an elementary substructure of ${\mathcal {B}}$ , then ${\mathcal {A}}\models \varphi$ if and only if ${\mathcal {B}}\models \varphi$ .
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Thus, an elementary substructure is a model of a theory exactly when the superstructure is a model.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] An embedding of a σ-structure ${\mathcal {A}}$ into another σ-structure ${\mathcal {B}}$ is a map *f*: *A* → *B* between the domains which can be written as an isomorphism of ${\mathcal {A}}$ with a substructure of ${\mathcal {B}}$ .
[src:model-theory/model-theory] If it can be written as an isomorphism with an elementary substructure, it is called an elementary embedding.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Every embedding is an injective homomorphism, but the converse holds only if the signature contains no relation symbols, such as in groups or fields.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] A field or a vector space can be regarded as a (commutative) group by simply ignoring some of its structure.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] The corresponding notion in model theory is that of a *reduct* of a structure to a subset of the original signature.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] The opposite relation is called an *expansion* - e.g. the (additive) group of the rational numbers, regarded as a structure in the signature {+,0} can be expanded to a field with the signature {×,+,1,0} or to an ordered group with the signature {+,0,<}.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Similarly, if σ' is a signature that extends another signature σ, then a complete σ'-theory can be restricted to σ by intersecting the set of its sentences with the set of σ-formulas.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Conversely, a complete σ-theory can be regarded as a σ'-theory, and one can extend it (in more than one way) to a complete σ'-theory.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] The terms reduct and expansion are sometimes applied to this relation as well.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] The compactness theorem states that a set of sentences S is satisfiable if every finite subset of S is satisfiable.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] The analogous statement with *consistent* instead of *satisfiable* is trivial, since every proof can have only a finite number of antecedents used in the proof.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] The completeness theorem allows us to transfer this to satisfiability.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] However, there are also several direct (semantic) proofs of the compactness theorem.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] As a corollary (i.e., its contrapositive), the compactness theorem says that every unsatisfiable first-order theory has a finite unsatisfiable subset.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] This theorem is of central importance in model theory, where the words "by compactness" are commonplace.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Another cornerstone of first-order model theory is the Löwenheim–Skolem theorem.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] According to the theorem, every infinite structure in a countable signature has a countable elementary substructure.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Conversely, for any infinite cardinal κ every infinite structure in a countable signature that is of cardinality less than κ can be elementarily embedded in another structure of cardinality κ (There is a straightforward generalisation to uncountable signatures).
[src:model-theory/model-theory] In particular, the Löwenheim-Skolem theorem implies that any theory in a countable signature with infinite models has a countable model as well as arbitrarily large models.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] In a certain sense made precise by Lindström's theorem, first-order logic is the most expressive logic for which both the Löwenheim–Skolem theorem and the compactness theorem hold.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] In model theory, definable sets are important objects of study.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] In a similar way, formulas with *n* free variables define subsets of ${\mathcal {M}}^{n}$ .
[src:model-theory/model-theory] defines the curve of all $(x,y)$ such that $y=x^{2}$ .
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Both of the definitions mentioned here are *parameter-free*, that is, the defining formulas don't mention any fixed domain elements.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] However, one can also consider definitions *with parameters from the model*.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] uses the parameter $\pi$ from $\mathbb {R}$ to define a curve.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] In general, definable sets without quantifiers are easy to describe, while definable sets involving possibly nested quantifiers can be much more complicated.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] If the theory of a structure has quantifier elimination, every set definable in a structure is definable by a quantifier-free formula over the same parameters as the original definition.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] For example, the theory of algebraically closed fields in the signature *σ*ring = (×,+,−,0,1) has quantifier elimination.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] This means that in an algebraically closed field, every formula is equivalent to a Boolean combination of equations between polynomials.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] If a theory does not have quantifier elimination, one can add additional symbols to its signature so that it does.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Axiomatisability and quantifier elimination results for specific theories, especially in algebra, were among the early landmark results of model theory.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] A theory *T* is called model-complete if every substructure of a model of *T* which is itself a model of *T* is an elementary substructure.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] There is a useful criterion for testing whether a substructure is an elementary substructure, called the Tarski–Vaught test.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] A theory that is not model-complete may have a model completion, which is a related model-complete theory that is not, in general, an extension of the original theory.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] A more general notion is that of a model companion.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Since we can negate this formula, every cofinite subset (which includes all but finitely many elements of the domain) is also always definable.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] This leads to the concept of a *minimal structure*.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] A structure ${\mathcal {M}}$ is called minimal if every subset $A\subseteq {\mathcal {M}}$ definable with parameters from ${\mathcal {M}}$ is either finite or cofinite.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] The corresponding concept at the level of theories is called *strong minimality*: A theory *T* is called strongly minimal if every model of *T* is minimal.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] A structure is called *strongly minimal* if the theory of that structure is strongly minimal.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Equivalently, a structure is strongly minimal if every elementary extension is minimal.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Since the theory of algebraically closed fields has quantifier elimination, every definable subset of an algebraically closed field is definable by a quantifier-free formula in one variable.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Quantifier-free formulas in one variable express Boolean combinations of polynomial equations in one variable, and since a nontrivial polynomial equation in one variable has only a finite number of solutions, the theory of algebraically closed fields is strongly minimal.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] This defines the subset of non-negative real numbers, which is neither finite nor cofinite.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] One can in fact use $\varphi$ to define arbitrary intervals on the real number line.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] It turns out that these suffice to represent every definable subset of $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:model-theory/model-theory] This generalisation of minimality has been very useful in the model theory of ordered structures.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] A densely totally ordered structure ${\mathcal {M}}$ in a signature including a symbol for the order relation is called o-minimal if every subset $A\subseteq {\mathcal {M}}$ definable with parameters from ${\mathcal {M}}$ is a finite union of points and intervals.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Particularly important are those definable sets that are also substructures, i. e. contain all constants and are closed under function application.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] For instance, one can study the definable subgroups of a certain group.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] However, there is no need to limit oneself to substructures in the same signature.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Since formulas with *n* free variables define subsets of ${\mathcal {M}}^{n}$ , *n*-ary relations can also be definable.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Functions are definable if the function graph is a definable relation, and constants $a\in {\mathcal {M}}$ are definable if there is a formula $\varphi (x)$ such that *a* is the only element of ${\mathcal {M}}$ such that $\varphi (a)$ is true.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] In this way, one can study definable groups and fields in general structures, for instance, which has been important in geometric stability theory.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] One can even go one step further, and move beyond immediate substructures.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Given a mathematical structure, there are very often associated structures which can be constructed as a quotient of part of the original structure via an equivalence relation.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] An important example is a quotient group of a group.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] One might say that to understand the full structure one must understand these quotients.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] When the equivalence relation is definable, we can give the previous sentence a precise meaning.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] We say that these structures are *interpretable*.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] A key fact is that one can translate sentences from the language of the interpreted structures to the language of the original structure.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Thus one can show that if a structure ${\mathcal {M}}$ interprets another whose theory is undecidable, then ${\mathcal {M}}$ itself is undecidable.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] For a sequence of elements $a_{1},\dots ,a_{n}$ of a structure ${\mathcal {M}}$ and a subset *A* of ${\mathcal {M}}$ , one can consider the set of all first-order formulas $\varphi (x_{1},\dots ,x_{n})$ with parameters in *A* that are satisfied by $a_{1},\dots ,a_{n}$ .
[src:model-theory/model-theory] This is called the *complete (n-)type realised by* $a_{1},\dots ,a_{n}$ *over A*.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] If there is an automorphism of ${\mathcal {M}}$ that is constant on *A* and sends $a_{1},\dots ,a_{n}$ to $b_{1},\dots ,b_{n}$ respectively, then $a_{1},\dots ,a_{n}$ and $b_{1},\dots ,b_{n}$ realise the same complete type over *A*.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] The real number line $\mathbb {R}$ , viewed as a structure with only the order relation {<}, will serve as a running example in this section.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Every element $a\in \mathbb {R}$ satisfies the same 1-type over the empty set.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] This is clear since any two real numbers *a* and *b* are connected by the order automorphism that shifts all numbers by *b-a*.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Over the subset $\mathbb {Z} \subseteq \mathbb {R}$ of integers, the 1-type of a non-integer real number *a* depends on its value rounded down to the nearest integer.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] More generally, whenever ${\mathcal {M}}$ is a structure and *A* a subset of ${\mathcal {M}}$ , a (partial) *n-type over A* is a set of formulas *p* with at most *n* free variables that are realised in an elementary extension ${\mathcal {N}}$ of ${\mathcal {M}}$ .
[src:model-theory/model-theory] If *p* contains every such formula or its negation, then *p* is *complete*.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] The set of complete *n*-types over *A* is often written as $S_{n}^{\mathcal {M}}(A)$ .
[src:model-theory/model-theory] If *A* is the empty set, then the type space only depends on the theory T of ${\mathcal {M}}$ .
[src:model-theory/model-theory] The notation $S_{n}(T)$ is commonly used for the set of types over the empty set consistent with T .
[src:model-theory/model-theory] If there is a single formula $\varphi$ such that the theory of ${\mathcal {M}}$ implies $\varphi \rightarrow \psi$ for every formula $\psi$ in *p*, then *p* is called *isolated*.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Since the real numbers $\mathbb {R}$ are Archimedean, there is no real number larger than every integer.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] However, a compactness argument shows that there is an elementary extension of the real number line in which there is an element larger than any integer.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Therefore, the set of formulas $\{n<x|n\in \mathbb {Z} \}$ is a 1-type over $\mathbb {Z} \subseteq \mathbb {R}$ that is not realised in the real number line $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:model-theory/model-theory] A subset of ${\mathcal {M}}^{n}$ that can be expressed as exactly those elements of ${\mathcal {M}}^{n}$ realising a certain type over *A* is called *type-definable* over *A*.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] For an algebraic example, suppose M is an algebraically closed field.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] This allows us to show that a type is determined exactly by the polynomial equations it contains.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Thus the set of complete n -types over a subfield A corresponds to the set of prime ideals of the polynomial ring $A[x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}]$ , and the type-definable sets are exactly the affine varieties.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] While not every type is realised in every structure, every structure realises its isolated types.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] If the only types over the empty set that are realised in a structure are the isolated types, then the structure is called *atomic*.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] On the other hand, no structure realises every type over every parameter set; if one takes all of ${\mathcal {M}}$ as the parameter set, then every 1-type over ${\mathcal {M}}$ realised in ${\mathcal {M}}$ is isolated by a formula of the form *a = x* for an $a\in {\mathcal {M}}$ .
[src:model-theory/model-theory] However, any proper elementary extension of ${\mathcal {M}}$ contains an element that is *not* in ${\mathcal {M}}$ .
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Therefore, a weaker notion has been introduced that captures the idea of a structure realising all types it could be expected to realise.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] A structure is called *saturated* if it realises every type over a parameter set $A\subset {\mathcal {M}}$ that is of smaller cardinality than ${\mathcal {M}}$ itself.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] While an automorphism that is constant on *A* will always preserve types over *A*, it is generally not true that any two sequences $a_{1},\dots ,a_{n}$ and $b_{1},\dots ,b_{n}$ that satisfy the same type over *A* can be mapped to each other by such an automorphism.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] A structure ${\mathcal {M}}$ in which this converse does hold for all *A* of smaller cardinality than ${\mathcal {M}}$ is called (strongly) **homogeneous**.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] The real number line is atomic in the language that contains only the order < , since all *n*-types over the empty set realised by $a_{1},\dots ,a_{n}$ in $\mathbb {R}$ are isolated by the order relations between the $a_{1},\dots ,a_{n}$ .
[src:model-theory/model-theory] It is not saturated, however, since it does not realise any 1-type over the countable set $\mathbb {Z}$ that implies *x* to be larger than any integer.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] The rational number line $\mathbb {Q}$ is saturated, in contrast, since $\mathbb {Q}$ is itself countable and therefore only has to realise types over finite subsets to be saturated.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] The set of definable subsets of ${\mathcal {M}}^{n}$ over some parameters A is a Boolean algebra.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] By Stone's representation theorem for Boolean algebras there is a natural dual topological space, which consists exactly of the complete n -types over A .
[src:model-theory/model-theory] The topology generated by sets of the form $\{p|\varphi \in p\}$ for single formulas $\varphi$ .
[src:model-theory/model-theory] This is called the *Stone space of n-types over A*.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] This topology explains some of the terminology used in model theory: The compactness theorem says that the Stone space is a compact topological space, and a type *p* is isolated if and only if *p* is an isolated point in the Stone topology.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] While types in algebraically closed fields correspond to the spectrum of the polynomial ring, the topology on the type space is the constructible topology: a set of types is basic open iff it is of the form $\{p:f(x)=0\in p\}$ or of the form $\{p:f(x)\neq 0\in p\}$ .
[src:model-theory/model-theory] This is finer than the Zariski topology.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Constructing models that realise certain types and do not realise others is an important task in model theory.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] be a countable set of non-isolated types over the empty set.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] This implies that if a theory in a countable signature has only countably many types over the empty set, then this theory has an atomic model.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] However, since the parameter set is fixed and there is no mention here of the cardinality of ${\mathcal {N}}$ , this does not imply that every theory has a saturated model.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] In fact, whether every theory has a saturated model is independent of the axioms of Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory, and is true if the generalised continuum hypothesis holds.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Ultraproducts are used as a general technique for constructing models that realise certain types.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] An *ultraproduct* is obtained from the direct product of a set of structures over an index set I by identifying those tuples that agree on almost all entries, where *almost all* is made precise by an ultrafilter U on I.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] An ultraproduct of copies of the same structure is known as an *ultrapower*.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] In particular, any ultraproduct of models of a theory is itself a model of that theory, and thus if two models have isomorphic ultrapowers, they are elementarily equivalent.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Therefore, ultraproducts provide a way to talk about elementary equivalence that avoids mentioning first-order theories at all.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Basic theorems of model theory such as the compactness theorem have alternative proofs using ultraproducts, and they can be used to construct saturated elementary extensions if they exist.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] A theory was originally called *categorical* if it determines a structure up to isomorphism.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] It turns out that this definition is not useful, due to serious restrictions in the expressivity of first-order logic.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] The Löwenheim–Skolem theorem implies that if a theory *T* has an infinite model for some infinite cardinal number, then it has a model of size κ for any sufficiently large cardinal number κ.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Since two models of different sizes cannot possibly be isomorphic, only finite structures can be described by a categorical theory.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] However, the weaker notion of κ-categoricity for a cardinal κ has become a key concept in model theory.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] A theory *T* is called *κ-categorical* if any two models of *T* that are of cardinality κ are isomorphic.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] It turns out that the question of κ-categoricity depends critically on whether κ is bigger than the cardinality of the language (i.e. $\aleph _{0}+|\sigma |$ , where |*σ*| is the cardinality of the signature).
[src:model-theory/model-theory] For finite or countable signatures this means that there is a fundamental difference between ω-cardinality and κ-cardinality for uncountable κ.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] For every natural number *n*, *Sn*(*T*) is finite.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] For every natural number *n*, the number of formulas *φ*(*x*1, ..., *x*n) in *n* free variables, up to equivalence modulo *T*, is finite.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] The theory of $(\mathbb {Q} ,<)$ , which is also the theory of $(\mathbb {R} ,<)$ , is ω-categorical, as every *n*-type $p(x_{1},\dots ,x_{n})$ over the empty set is isolated by the pairwise order relation between the $x_{i}$ .
[src:model-theory/model-theory] This means that every countable dense linear order is order-isomorphic to the rational number line.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] On the other hand, the theories of ℚ, ℝ and ℂ as fields are not $\omega$ -categorical.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] This follows from the fact that in all those fields, any of the infinitely many natural numbers can be defined by a formula of the form $x=1+\dots +1$ .
[src:model-theory/model-theory] The equivalent characterisations of this subsection, due independently to Engeler, Ryll-Nardzewski and Svenonius, are sometimes referred to as the Ryll-Nardzewski theorem.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] In combinatorial signatures, a common source of ω-categorical theories are Fraïssé limits, which are obtained as the limit of amalgamating all possible configurations of a class of finite relational structures.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Michael Morley showed in 1963 that there is only one notion of *uncountable categoricity* for theories in countable languages.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Morley's proof revealed deep connections between uncountable categoricity and the internal structure of the models, which became the starting point of classification theory and stability theory.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Uncountably categorical theories are from many points of view the most well-behaved theories.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] In particular, complete strongly minimal theories are uncountably categorical.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] This shows that the theory of algebraically closed fields of a given characteristic is uncountably categorical, with the transcendence degree of the field determining its isomorphism type.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] A theory that is both ω-categorical and uncountably categorical is called *totally categorical*.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] A key factor in the structure of the class of models of a first-order theory is its place in the *stability hierarchy*.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] A theory is called *stable* if it is $\lambda$ -stable for some infinite cardinal $\lambda$ .
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Traditionally, theories that are $\aleph _{0}$ -stable are called *$\omega$ -stable*.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] *T* is $\lambda$ -stable if and only if $\lambda ^{\aleph _{0}}=\lambda$ (see Cardinal exponentiation for an explanation of $\lambda ^{\aleph _{0}}$ ).
[src:model-theory/model-theory] *T* is $\lambda$ -stable for any $\lambda \geq 2^{\aleph _{0}}$ (where $2^{\aleph _{0}}$ is the cardinality of the continuum).
[src:model-theory/model-theory] A theory of the first type is called *unstable*, a theory of the second type is called *strictly stable* and a theory of the third type is called *superstable*.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Furthermore, if a theory is $\omega$ -stable, it is stable in every infinite cardinal, so $\omega$ -stability is stronger than superstability.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Many constructions in model theory are easier when restricted to stable theories; for instance, every model of a stable theory has a saturated elementary extension, regardless of whether the generalised continuum hypothesis is true.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Shelah's original motivation for studying stable theories was to decide how many models a countable theory has of any uncountable cardinality.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] If a theory is uncountably categorical, then it is $\omega$ -stable.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] More generally, the *Main gap theorem* implies that if there is an uncountable cardinal $\lambda$ such that a theory *T* has less than $2^{\lambda }$ models of cardinality $\lambda$ , then *T* is superstable.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] The stability hierarchy is also crucial for analysing the geometry of definable sets within a model of a theory.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] In $\omega$ -stable theories, *Morley rank* is an important dimension notion for definable sets *S* within a model.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] A theory *T* in which every definable set has well-defined Morley rank is called *totally transcendental*; if *T* is countable, then *T* is totally transcendental if and only if *T* is $\omega$ -stable.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Morley Rank can be extended to types by setting the Morley rank of a type to be the minimum of the Morley ranks of the formulas in the type.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Thus, one can also speak of the Morley rank of an element *a* over a parameter set *A*, defined as the Morley rank of the type of *a* over *A*.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] There are also analogues of Morley rank which are well-defined if and only if a theory is superstable (U-rank) or merely stable (Shelah's $\infty$ -rank).
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Those dimension notions can be used to define notions of independence and of generic extensions.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] More recently, stability has been decomposed into simplicity and "not the independence property" (NIP).
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Simple theories are those theories in which a well-behaved notion of independence can be defined, while NIP theories generalise o-minimal structures.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] They are related to stability since a theory is stable if and only if it is NIP and simple, and various aspects of stability theory have been generalised to theories in one of these classes.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Model-theoretic results have been generalised beyond elementary classes, that is, classes axiomatisable by a first-order theory.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Model theory in higher-order logics or infinitary logics is hampered by the fact that completeness and compactness do not in general hold for these logics.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] This is made concrete by Lindström's theorem, stating roughly that first-order logic is essentially the strongest logic in which both the Löwenheim-Skolem theorems and compactness hold.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] However, model theoretic techniques have been developed extensively for these logics too.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] It turns out, however, that much of the model theory of more expressive logical languages is independent of Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] More recently, alongside the shift in focus to complete stable and categorical theories, there has been work on classes of models defined semantically rather than axiomatised by a logical theory.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] One example is *homogeneous model theory*, which studies the class of substructures of arbitrarily large homogeneous models.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Fundamental results of stability theory and geometric stability theory generalise to this setting.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] As a generalisation of strongly minimal theories, quasiminimally excellent classes are those in which every definable set is either countable or co-countable.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] They are key to the model theory of the complex exponential function.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] The most general semantic framework in which stability is studied are abstract elementary classes, which are defined by a *strong substructure* relation generalising that of an elementary substructure.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Even though its definition is purely semantic, every abstract elementary class can be presented as the models of a first-order theory which omit certain types.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Generalising stability-theoretic notions to abstract elementary classes is an ongoing research program.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Among the early successes of model theory are Tarski's proofs of quantifier elimination for various algebraically interesting classes, such as the real closed fields, Boolean algebras and algebraically closed fields of a given characteristic.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] In the 1960s, the introduction of the ultraproduct construction led to new applications in algebra.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] This includes Ax's work on pseudofinite fields, proving that the theory of finite fields is decidable, and Ax and Kochen's proof of as special case of Artin's conjecture on diophantine equations, the Ax–Kochen theorem.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] The ultraproduct construction also led to Abraham Robinson's development of nonstandard analysis, which aims to provide a rigorous calculus of infinitesimals.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] In 2011, Jonathan Pila applied techniques around o-minimality to prove the André–Oort conjecture for products of Modular curves.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] In a separate strand of inquiries that also grew around stable theories, Laskowski showed in 1992 that NIP theories describe exactly those definable classes that are PAC-learnable in machine learning theory.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] This has led to several interactions between these separate areas.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] In 2018, the correspondence was extended as Hunter and Chase showed that stable theories correspond to online learnable classes.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Model theory as a subject has existed since approximately the middle of the 20th century, and the term "theory of models" was coined by Alfred Tarski, a member of the Lwów–Warsaw school, in 1954.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] However some earlier research, especially in mathematical logic, is often regarded as being of a model-theoretical nature in retrospect.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] The first significant result in what is now model theory was a special case of the downward Löwenheim–Skolem theorem, published by Leopold Löwenheim in 1915.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] The compactness theorem was implicit in work by Thoralf Skolem, but it was first published in 1930, as a lemma in Kurt Gödel's proof of his completeness theorem.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] The Löwenheim–Skolem theorem and the compactness theorem received their respective general forms in 1936 and 1941 from Anatoly Maltsev.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] The development of model theory as an independent discipline was brought on by Alfred Tarski during the interbellum.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Tarski's work included logical consequence, deductive systems, the algebra of logic, the theory of definability, and the semantic definition of truth, among other topics.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] His semantic methods culminated in the model theory he and a number of his Berkeley students developed in the 1950s and '60s.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] In the further history of the discipline, different strands began to emerge, and the focus of the subject shifted.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] In the 1960s, techniques around ultraproducts became a popular tool in model theory.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] At the same time, researchers such as James Ax were investigating the first-order model theory of various algebraic classes, and others such as H.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Jerome Keisler were extending the concepts and results of first-order model theory to other logical systems.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Then, inspired by Morley's problem, Shelah developed stability theory.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] His work around stability changed the complexion of model theory, giving rise to a whole new class of concepts.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Over the next decades, it became clear that the resulting stability hierarchy is closely connected to the geometry of sets that are definable in those models; this gave rise to the subdiscipline now known as geometric stability theory.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] An example of an influential proof from geometric model theory is Hrushovski's proof of the Mordell–Lang conjecture for function fields.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Finite model theory, which concentrates on finite structures, diverges significantly from the study of infinite structures in both the problems studied and the techniques used.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] In particular, many central results of classical model theory fail when restricted to finite structures.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] This includes the compactness theorem, Gödel's completeness theorem, and the method of ultraproducts for first-order logic.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] At the interface of finite and infinite model theory are algorithmic or computable model theory and the study of 0-1 laws, where the infinite models of a generic theory of a class of structures provide information on the distribution of finite models.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Prominent application areas of FMT are descriptive complexity theory, database theory and formal language theory.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Any set theory (which is expressed in a countable language), if it is consistent, has a countable model; this is known as Skolem's paradox, since there are sentences in set theory which postulate the existence of uncountable sets and yet these sentences are true in our countable model.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Particularly the proof of the independence of the continuum hypothesis requires considering sets in models which appear to be uncountable when viewed from *within* the model, but are countable to someone *outside* the model.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] In the other direction, model theory is itself formalised within Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] For instance, the development of the fundamentals of model theory (such as the compactness theorem) rely on the axiom of choice, and is in fact equivalent over Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory without choice to the Boolean prime ideal theorem.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Other results in model theory depend on set-theoretic axioms beyond the standard ZFC framework.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] For example, if the Continuum Hypothesis holds then every countable model has an ultrapower which is saturated (in its own cardinality).
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Similarly, if the Generalized Continuum Hypothesis holds then every model has a saturated elementary extension.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Neither of these results are provable in ZFC alone.
[src:model-theory/model-theory] Finally, some questions arising from model theory (such as compactness for infinitary logics) have been shown to be equivalent to large cardinal axioms.
[src:model-theory/quantifier-elimination] One way of classifying formulas is by the amount of quantification.
[src:model-theory/quantifier-elimination] Formulas with less depth of quantifier alternation are thought of as being simpler, with the quantifier-free formulas as the simplest.
[src:model-theory/quantifier-elimination] A theory has quantifier elimination if for every formula $\alpha$ , there exists another formula $\alpha _{QF}$ without quantifiers that is equivalent to it (modulo this theory).
[src:model-theory/quantifier-elimination] Here the sentence on the left-hand side involves a quantifier $\exists x\in \mathbb {R}$ , whereas the equivalent sentence on the right does not.
[src:model-theory/quantifier-elimination] Quantifier elimination for the theory of the real numbers as an ordered additive group is *Fourier–Motzkin elimination*; for the theory of the field of real numbers it is the *Tarski–Seidenberg theorem*.
[src:model-theory/quantifier-elimination] Quantifier elimination can also be used to show that "combining" decidable theories leads to new decidable theories (see Feferman–Vaught theorem).
[src:model-theory/quantifier-elimination] If a theory has quantifier elimination, then a specific question can be addressed: Is there a method of determining $\alpha _{QF}$ for each $\alpha$ ?
[src:model-theory/quantifier-elimination] If there is such a method we call it a quantifier elimination algorithm.
[src:model-theory/quantifier-elimination] If there is such an algorithm, then decidability for the theory reduces to deciding the truth of the quantifier-free sentences.
[src:model-theory/quantifier-elimination] Various model-theoretic ideas are related to quantifier elimination, and there are various equivalent conditions.
[src:model-theory/quantifier-elimination] Every first-order theory with quantifier elimination is model complete.
[src:model-theory/quantifier-elimination] Conversely, a model-complete theory, whose theory of universal consequences has the amalgamation property, has quantifier elimination.
[src:model-theory/quantifier-elimination] The models of the theory of the universal consequences of a theory T are precisely the substructures of the models of T .
[src:model-theory/quantifier-elimination] The theory of linear orders does not have quantifier elimination.
[src:model-theory/quantifier-elimination] However the theory of its universal consequences has the amalgamation property.
[src:model-theory/quantifier-elimination] where each $L_{i}$ is a literal, is equivalent to a quantifier-free formula.
[src:model-theory/quantifier-elimination] In early model theory, quantifier elimination was used to demonstrate that various theories possess properties like decidability and completeness.
[src:model-theory/quantifier-elimination] A common technique was to show first that a theory admits elimination of quantifiers and thereafter prove decidability or completeness by considering only the quantifier-free formulas.
[src:model-theory/quantifier-elimination] This technique can be used to show that Presburger arithmetic is decidable.
[src:model-theory/quantifier-elimination] Theories could be decidable yet not admit quantifier elimination.
[src:model-theory/quantifier-elimination] Strictly speaking, the theory of the additive natural numbers did not admit quantifier elimination, but it was an expansion of the additive natural numbers that was shown to be decidable.
[src:model-theory/quantifier-elimination] Example: Nullstellensatz for algebraically closed fields and for differentially closed fields.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] The **ultraproduct** is a mathematical construction that appears mainly in abstract algebra and mathematical logic, in particular in model theory and set theory.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] An ultraproduct is the quotient set of the direct product of a family of structures.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] All factors need to have the same signature.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] The **ultrapower** is the special case of this construction in which all factors are equal.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] For example, ultrapowers can be used to construct new fields from given ones.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] A special case of this is the ultrapower of the real numbers, which satisfies the conditions for the hyperreal numbers.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] When ${\mathcal {U}}$ is a principal ultrafilter (which happens if and only if ${\mathcal {U}}$ contains its kernel $\cap \,{\mathcal {U}}$ ) then the ultraproduct is isomorphic to one of the factors.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] The ultraproduct acts as a filter product space where elements are equal if they are equal only at the filtered components (non-filtered components are ignored under the equivalence).
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] One may define a finitely additive measure m on the index set I by saying $m(A)=1$ if $A\in {\mathcal {U}}$ and $m(A)=0$ otherwise.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] Then two members of the Cartesian product are equivalent precisely if they are equal almost everywhere on the index set.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] The ultraproduct is the set of equivalence classes thus generated.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] Finitary operations on the Cartesian product ${\textstyle \prod \limits _{i\in I}}M_{i}$ are defined pointwise (for example, if + is a binary function then $a_{i}+b_{i}=(a+b)_{i}$ ).
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] An *ultrapower* is an ultraproduct for which all the factors $M_{i}$ are equal.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] The hyperreal numbers are the ultraproduct of one copy of the real numbers for every natural number, with regard to an ultrafilter over the natural numbers containing all cofinite sets.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] Their order is the extension of the order of the real numbers.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] For example, the sequence $\omega$ given by $\omega _{i}=i$ defines an equivalence class representing a hyperreal number that is greater than any real number.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] Analogously, one can define nonstandard integers, nonstandard complex numbers, etc., by taking the ultraproduct of copies of the corresponding structures.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] However, let $\chi _{i}=i$ for i not equal to $7,$ but $\chi _{7}=8.$ The set of indices on which $\omega$ and $\chi$ agree is a member of any ultrafilter (because $\omega$ and $\chi$ agree almost everywhere), so $\omega$ and $\chi$ belong to the same equivalence class.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] Łoś's theorem, also called *the fundamental theorem of ultraproducts*, is due to Jerzy Łoś (the surname is pronounced [ˈwɔɕ], approximately "wash", or [ˈɫɔɕ]).
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] Let $\sigma$ be a signature, ${\mathcal {U}}$ be an ultrafilter over a set $I,$ and for each $i\in I$ let $M_{i}$ be a $\sigma$ -structure.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] The theorem is proved by induction on the complexity of the formula $\phi .$ The fact that ${\mathcal {U}}$ is an ultrafilter (and not just a filter) is used in the negation clause, and the axiom of choice is needed at the existential quantifier step.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] As an application, one obtains the transfer theorem for hyperreal fields.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] Let R be a unary relation in the structure $M,$ and form the ultrapower of M .
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] Then the set $S=\{x\in M:Rx\}$ has an analog ${}^{*}S$ in the ultrapower, and first-order formulas involving S are also valid for ${}^{*}S.$ For example, let M be the reals, and let $Rx$ hold if x is a rational number.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] Then in M we can say that for any pair of rationals x and $y,$ there exists another number z such that z is not rational, and $x<z<y.$ Since this can be translated into a first-order logical formula in the relevant formal language, Łoś's theorem implies that ${}^{*}S$ has the same property.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] That is, we can define a notion of the hyperrational numbers, which are a subset of the hyperreals, and they have the same first-order properties as the rationals.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] In fact, the Archimedean property is false for the hyperreals, as shown by the construction of the hyperreal number $\omega$ above.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] In model theory and set theory, the direct limit of a sequence of ultrapowers is often considered.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] In model theory, this construction can be referred to as an **ultralimit** or **limiting ultrapower**.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] Beginning with a structure, $A_{0}$ and an ultrafilter, ${\mathcal {D}}_{0},$ form an ultrapower, $A_{1}.$ Then repeat the process to form $A_{2},$ and so forth.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] For each n there is a canonical diagonal embedding $A_{n}\to A_{n+1}.$ At limit stages, such as $A_{\omega },$ form the direct limit of earlier stages.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] The ultrafilter monad is the codensity monad of the inclusion of the category of finite sets into the category of all sets.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] Similarly, the ultraproduct monad is the codensity monad of the inclusion of the category $\mathbf {FinFam}$ of finitely-indexed families of sets into the category $\mathbf {Fam}$ of all indexed families of sets.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] So in this sense, ultraproducts are categorically inevitable.
[src:model-theory/ultraproduct] Explicitly, an object of $\mathbf {Fam}$ consists of a non-empty index set I and an indexed family $\left(M_{i}\right)_{i\in I}$ of sets.
